The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Panel to hear charges in January
                                                                                                                       7                                      Panel to hear charges in January
            A STAFF REPORTER                      
	Calcutta: The International Cricket Council (ICC) has constituted a three-member independent anti-corruption tribunal to hear the alleged spot-fixing charges against three suspended Pakistani players  Salman Butt, Mohammed Asif and Mohammed Aamer  in January, according to a media release.         
	The three-member tribunal will be made up of Beloff QC (as Chair), together with two other Code of Conduct Commissioners  Justice Albie Sachs from South Africa and Sharad Rao from Kenya  as per the appointment procedure described in the ICCs Anti-Corruption Code.         
	During a telephone hearing, it was also agreed that the full hearing would be scheduled to take place from Januray 6-11, 2011 in Doha.         
	The three players were charged under Article 2 of the ICC Anti-Corruption Code on September 2 and have been provisionally suspended since that date. Butt and Aamer had an appeal against that provisional suspension dismissed on October 31.                                                                                                                     
